[[sn:Kyūman]]
[[ja:灸まん]]

{{出典の明記|date=2024th year 5月}} [[File:Kyu-Man.jpg|thumbnail|240px|Kyūman]] '''{{ill|Kyūman|ja|灸まん|qq=draft}}''' is a type of '''wagashi (Japanese confectionery)''' produced by '''{{ill|Kyūman Honpo Ishidanya|ja|灸まん本舗石段や|qq=draft}}''' (Konpira-dō Co., Ltd.) in '''{{ill|Kotohira, Kagawa|ja|琴平町|qq=draft}}''', a town famous for '''{{ill|Kotohira-gū|ja|金刀比羅宮|1=Kotohira-gū|qq=draft}}''' (commonly known as '''Konpira-san'''). It is one of the most '''popular souvenirs for visitors to Kotohira Shrine''', alongside '''{{ill|Meibutsu Kamado|ja|名物かまど|qq=draft}}''', and is considered a '''representative souvenir of Kagawa Prefecture'''.
== Overview == As its name suggests, '''Kyūman is shaped like an "okyū" (moxibustion)''', resembling '''a slightly conical manju (steamed bun)''' with a rounded top. The filling consists of '''egg yolk-based sweet bean paste'''. The package design was created by '''painter {{ill|Wada Kunbō|ja|和田邦坊|qq=draft}}''', a native of Kotohira Town.
The shop '''Ishidanya''' originated as '''"Asadaya Kyuhachi,"''' a '''ryokan (inn)''' established along the stone steps leading to Kotohira Shrine in '''1765''' (Meiwa 2). During the '''Tenpō era''', a famous '''Edo-period yakuza''' named '''Koganei Kojirō''' stayed at this inn. He requested that the '''maidservants''' apply the '''famous Konpira moxibustion''' on him. As Kojirō was a '''handsome man''', the '''maids competed''' for the chance to apply the treatment. Eventually, one of the maids applied a '''gentler version of the moxibustion''', to which Kojirō remarked, '''"This is a sweet moxibustion"''', a phrase that gained popularity and further boosted the reputation of '''Konpira's moxibustion'''.
The '''sixth-generation owner''' of Asadaya renamed the business '''Ishidanya''' and transitioned from an '''inn to a teahouse'''. Inspired by this '''yakuza legend''', he '''created a bun in the shape of a moxibustion cone''', which became the '''origin of Kyūman'''. To this day, '''Ishidanya's main store''' remains '''one of the oldest buildings along the Kotohira Shrine approach'''.
In '''2002''', Kyūman received the '''Grand Prize (Honorary Presidential Award)''' at the '''24th National Confectionery Expo''' held in '''Kumamoto City'''. It is also '''served as a tea confectionery''' at '''{{ill|Kikugetsutei|ja|掬月亭|qq=draft}}''', a '''teahouse located within {{ill|Ritsurin Garden|ja|栗林公園|qq=draft}} in Takamatsu City'''.
Besides Kyūman, '''Konpira-dō Co., Ltd.''' also operates: - '''"Kyūman Udon"''', specializing in the production and sale of '''{{ill|Sanuki Udon|ja|讃岐うどん|qq=draft}}'''. - '''"Kyūman Art Museum"''', located in the neighboring city of '''{{ill|Zentsūji, Kagawa|ja|善通寺市|qq=draft}}''', which features an exhibition on '''Wada Kunbō's works'''.
== External Links == * [http://www.kyuman.co.jp/ Kyūman Honpo Ishidanya - Official Website]
